# AI DevOS — Architecture Decisions (ADRs)

Version: 1.0

---

# Purpose

This document records the major architectural decisions behind AI DevOS.

Unlike implementation documents, ADRs explain **why** the architecture was designed this way.

Each decision includes:

- Problem
- Decision
- Alternatives
- Consequences

---

# ADR-001

## Stateless Agents

### Problem

Agents performing multiple responsibilities become difficult to maintain.

Examples

- memory loading
- prompt building
- workflow updates
- provider communication

Such agents quickly become tightly coupled.

---

### Decision

Every agent in AI DevOS is completely stateless.

Agents only transform

```
ExecutionContext

↓

StageArtifact
```

---

### Alternatives Considered

Stateful agents

Pros

- fewer framework classes

Cons

- hidden state
- poor testing
- tight coupling
- difficult retries

---

### Consequences

Advantages

✓ deterministic execution

✓ reusable agents

✓ simpler testing

✓ provider independence

Tradeoff

More orchestration classes.

---

# ADR-002

## Centralized Memory Management

### Problem

Allowing every subsystem to write memory independently causes inconsistent knowledge.

---

### Decision

Only MemoryManager owns memory.

Writing path

```
Artifact

↓

Extraction Pipeline

↓

Memory Manager

↓

Provider
```

---

### Alternatives

Agents writing memory directly.

Rejected because

- duplicated formats
- inconsistent ownership
- memory corruption

---

### Consequences

✓ single ownership

✓ standardized memories

✓ easier migration

---

# ADR-003

## Workspace Registry Instead of Repository Scanning

### Problem

Scanning the repository before every execution is expensive.

Large repositories increase latency.

---

### Decision

Maintain a Workspace Registry containing indexed metadata.

The Context Framework queries the registry instead of scanning files.

---

### Alternatives

Filesystem traversal

Rejected.

Repository RAG

Rejected as primary strategy.

---

### Consequences

✓ deterministic execution

✓ faster context building

✓ scalable repositories

Tradeoff

Registry must remain synchronized.

---

# ADR-004

## Context Builder Owns Context Construction

### Problem

Agents building their own context causes duplication and inconsistent prompts.

---

### Decision

Only ContextBuilder constructs AgentContext.

Agents receive fully prepared context.

---

### Alternatives

Each agent loads memory independently.

Rejected.

---

### Consequences

✓ one source of truth

✓ reusable context logic

✓ simpler agents

---

# ADR-005

## Provider Abstraction

### Problem

Direct provider usage couples business logic to one AI vendor.

---

### Decision

Introduce

```
LLMManager

↓

LLMRuntime

↓

ProviderFactory

↓

BaseProvider
```

---

### Alternatives

Direct Gemini SDK.

Direct Ollama API.

Rejected.

---

### Consequences

✓ provider independence

✓ future extensibility

✓ vendor replacement

---

# ADR-006

## Separate Generation From Review

### Problem

An agent cannot objectively evaluate its own work.

---

### Decision

Introduce an independent Review Framework.

```
Agent

↓

Reviewer

↓

Approved?
```

---

### Alternatives

Self-review.

Rejected.

---

### Consequences

✓ higher quality

✓ retry support

✓ better architecture

---

# ADR-007

## Stage Session Is Temporary

### Problem

Permanent conversations consume memory and leak obsolete context.

---

### Decision

StageSession exists only while a stage executes.

Destroyed immediately after approval.

---

### Alternatives

Persistent conversations.

Rejected.

---

### Consequences

✓ predictable execution

✓ reduced memory

✓ isolated retries

---

# ADR-008

## Approved Knowledge Only

### Problem

Rejected artifacts should never become project knowledge.

---

### Decision

Only approved artifacts enter long-term memory.

Rejected artifacts remain inside StageSession only.

---

### Consequences

✓ clean knowledge base

✓ reliable retrieval

---

# ADR-009

## One Responsibility Per Framework

### Problem

Large frameworks become difficult to evolve.

---

### Decision

Each framework owns one subsystem.

Examples

Workflow

Execution

Memory

Review

Workspace

LLM

Context

---

### Consequences

✓ low coupling

✓ independent evolution

✓ easier testing

---

# ADR-010

## Metadata Instead of Source Code

### Problem

Loading complete repositories into prompts is expensive.

---

### Decision

Workspace Registry stores metadata only.

Source code remains on disk.

---

### Consequences

✓ lightweight context

✓ scalable projects

Tradeoff

Future source retrieval still required.

---

# ADR-011

## Runtime Memory Is Separate

### Problem

Temporary execution state should not pollute project knowledge.

---

### Decision

Runtime Memory exists independently from Long-Term Memory.

Destroyed after execution.

---

### Consequences

✓ clean knowledge

✓ isolated retries

✓ deterministic execution

---

# ADR-012

## Prompt Templates Outside Python

### Problem

Hardcoded prompts are difficult to maintain.

---

### Decision

Store prompts as Markdown templates.

Load using PromptLoader.

---

### Consequences

✓ versionable prompts

✓ editable by non-developers

✓ cleaner code

---

# ADR-013

## Configuration Outside Code

### Problem

Embedding provider configuration inside source code prevents deployment flexibility.

---

### Decision

Externalize configuration.

Examples

- config.yaml

- .env

---

### Consequences

✓ environment independence

✓ cloud readiness

---

# ADR-014

## Explicit Dependency Direction

### Decision

Dependencies always flow downward.

```
API

↓

Workflow

↓

Execution

↓

Context

↓

Agent

↓

LLM

↓

Provider
```

Reverse dependencies are prohibited.

---

### Consequences

✓ no circular imports

✓ modular design

---

# ADR-015

## Framework-Driven Architecture

### Decision

AI DevOS is designed as cooperating frameworks rather than one monolithic application.

Frameworks

- Workflow

- Context

- Agent

- LLM

- Review

- Memory

- Workspace

- Execution

Each framework evolves independently.

---

# Summary

These Architecture Decision Records document the reasoning behind AI DevOS.

As the project evolves, new ADRs should be added whenever significant architectural decisions are made.

Existing ADRs should never be silently modified; instead, new ADRs should supersede earlier ones while preserving the historical rationale behind the system's evolution.